</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B723428AED54647774F15EA9883AE382" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="D73509C62DABDD75133D30B544510EF2" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="66EC8AA1129BECDC5EF78DCDE5077E54" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">
A rare species generally found in disturbed habitats, especially on disturbed soil and concrete, and possibly introduced from the northern hemisphere. There is only one record from Chile in disturbed habitats in the capitol Santiago (
<bibRefCitation id="3ECE192899E41C369236D1FCF5A5172F" author="Ochi, H" journalOrPublisher="Hikobia" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" pagination="221 - 223" refId="B19" refString="Ochi, H, Mahu, M, 1988. Supplement to the Bryoideae (Bryaceae, Musci) in South America. Hikobia 10: 221 - 223" title="Supplement to the Bryoideae (Bryaceae, Musci) in South America." volume="10" year="1988">Ochi and Mahu 1988</bibRefCitation>
, at HO, not seen!). It is characterized by its dioicous sexual condition, rosulate to somewhat evenly foliate stems, small leaves that are irregularly contorted when dry, costa excurrent into a medium-length awn, a narrow but usually distinct limbidium, and serrulate distal leaf margins. The plants are often reddish-tinged. The rhizoidal tubers are diagnostic; predominantly red, with strongly protuberant cell walls, from 100-280 
<normalizedToken id="101D408EDADB3C6FD0A9926B3DF564A1" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
in diameter, often arising from lower leaf axils or at the base of the stem on short rhizoids. The species has a scattered world-wide temperate distribution (Illustrations: 
<bibRefCitation id="2848103150DEE334B53E5FACA676D9B4" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1179/006813864804812128" author="Crundwell, AC" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the British Bryological Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" pagination="597 - 637" refId="B2" refString="Crundwell, AC, Nyholm, E, 1964. The European species of the Bryum erythrocarpum complex. Transactions of the British Bryological Society 4 (4): 597 - 637, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1179/006813864804812128" title="The European species of the Bryum erythrocarpum complex." url="https://doi.org/10.1179/006813864804812128" volume="4" year="1964">Crundwell and Nyholm 1964</bibRefCitation>
: 630, as 
<taxonomicName id="91078139A09703BA58077E5C382A60CF" authorityName="Mitten" authorityYear="1856" class="Bryopsida" family="Bryaceae" genus="Bryum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Bryum rubens" order="Bryales" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="species" species="rubens">
<emphasis id="9F3D0F06B0EA02286FA404C21190E65C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Bryum rubens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="F5A60CB28585946EC35C57F23FD48100" author="Lueth, M" journalOrPublisher="Bryologie" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" refId="B10" refString="Lueth, M, 2019. Mosses of Europe. A Photographic Flora. Vol. 3. M. Lueth Publications, Freiburg, Germany, 844-1533." title="Mosses of Europe. A Photographic Flora. Vol. 3. M. Lueth Publications, Freiburg, Germany, 844 - 1533." year="2019">
<normalizedToken id="398CA4CA5438B9448D9F12C9B7F5B0E0" originalValue="Lüth">Lueth</normalizedToken>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
: 938 as 
<taxonomicName id="0EE61DE32A2E3084027015FE1A664CED" class="Bryopsida" family="Bryaceae" genus="Ptychostomum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ptychostomum rubens" order="Scuticociliatida" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="species" species="rubens">
<emphasis id="613435A0070016D3326B1A0E978D5936" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Ptychostomum rubens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="90E35B0CFFDD499505DE9CCF6D01392C" author="Holyoak, DT" journalOrPublisher="Phytotaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" refId="B6" refString="Holyoak, DT, 2021. European Bryaceae. A Guide to the Species of the Moss Family Bryaceae in Western &amp; Central Europe and Macaronesia. Pisces Publications, Newberry, Berkshire, UK, 1-344." title="European Bryaceae. A Guide to the Species of the Moss Family Bryaceae in Western &amp; Central Europe and Macaronesia. Pisces Publications, Newberry, Berkshire, UK, 1 - 344." year="2021">Holyoak 2021</bibRefCitation>
: 232, as 
<taxonomicName id="321AB8F1B5EA8CFA4FA2D1A1452E5355" genus="P." lsidName="P. rubens" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" rank="species" species="rubens">
<emphasis id="EC7EB545978901A90491099734F3B65D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">P. rubens</emphasis>
